<subsection xml:id="subsec-volume-of-pyramids" xmlns:xi="http://www.w3.org/2001/XInclude">
    <title>Volume of Pyramids</title>
    <objectives component="outcomes">
        <introduction xml:id="auto_9lbxz8q1">
            <p xml:id="auto_azt6s849">
            <dl>
                <li xml:id="auto_saq4byly">
                    <title>Strand</title>
                    <p xml:id="auto_1eb62g7w">
                        2.0 Measurements and Geometry
                    </p>
                </li>
                <li xml:id="auto_qmiv5cun">
                    <title>Sub-Strand</title>
                    <p xml:id="auto_nlcvtfpg">
                        2.8 Volume
                    </p>
                </li>
                <li xml:id="auto_2ed6eyjc">
                    <title>Specific Learning Outcomes</title>
                    <p xml:id="auto_kh3cx1jt">
                        Calculate the volume of pyramids using the formula <m>V = \frac{1}{3} \times \text{Base Area} \times h</m>
                    </p>
                </li>
                <li xml:id="auto_gvttgd7j" component="lesson-plan">
                    <title>Grade Level</title>
                    <p xml:id="auto_id1u36jx">
                        10
                    </p>
                </li>
                <li xml:id="auto_urd7nbxc" component="lesson-plan">
                    <title>Estimated Duration</title>
                    <p xml:id="auto_bx8we3rb">
                        40 minutes
                    </p>
                </li>
            </dl>
            </p>
            <p xml:id="auto_33ij9zbf" component="lesson-plan">
                <p xml:id="auto_wschvly0"> Upon completion of this lesson, learners will be able to:
                <ol>
                    <li xml:id="auto_c612zu9u">
                        <p xml:id="auto_r566h4pe">
                            <alert>Know (Conceptual Understanding):</alert> Define a pyramid and explain why its volume is one-third that of a prism with the same base and height.
                        </p>
                    </li>
                    <li xml:id="auto_jjfz9l1y">
                        <p xml:id="auto_4ch83m5x">
                            <alert>Do (Procedural Skill):</alert> Calculate the volume of square, rectangular, and triangular pyramids using <m>V = \frac{1}{3} \times \text{Base Area} \times h</m>.
                        </p>
                    </li>
                    <li xml:id="auto_2ur2fph2">
                        <p xml:id="auto_vu8dmhc4">
                            <alert>Apply (Application/Problem-Solving):</alert> Solve real-world problems involving pyramid volumes, such as tent structures and architectural designs.
                        </p>
                    </li>
                </ol>
                </p>
            </p>
        </introduction>
    </objectives>
        <axiom component="resources">
        <!-- Link to blurb -->
        <xi:include href="../../resources-blurb-lesson.ptx" />

        <sbsgroup widths="45% 45%" margins="2% 2%">
            <sidebyside>
                <p xml:id="auto_bqafcapm">
                    <dataurl source="lesson_plans/measurements-and-geometry/volume/volume-of-pyramids.pdf"> Lesson Plan </dataurl>
                </p>
                <p xml:id="auto_90wg7jn0">
                    <dataurl source="lesson_plans/measurements-and-geometry/volume/step-by-step-guide_volume-of-pyramids.pdf"> Step-by-Step Guide </dataurl>
                </p>
            </sidebyside>
        </sbsgroup>
    </axiom>
    <xi:include href="../../resources-materials.ptx" />

    <axiom component="lesson-plan">
        <title>Problem-Solving and Discovery</title>
        <p xml:id="auto_eo2yngqo">
            <alert>Expected Time:</alert> 15 minutes
        </p>
        <p xml:id="auto_tv1o6r4y">
            <alert>Grouping:</alert> Organise learners into small groups. Distribute pictures of famous pyramids, measuring tape or rulers, and small model or LEGO pyramids.
        </p>
        <p xml:id="auto_s1k9ukjq">
            <alert>Teacher Facilitation Questions:</alert>
        </p>
        <p xml:id="auto_clf2h18m">
            <ul>
                <li xml:id="auto_tybyifk3">
                    <p xml:id="auto_nbgeohm2"><q>What do you notice about these structures? What shape is the base? What shape are the faces?</q></p>
                </li>
                <li xml:id="auto_qjgw08hv">
                    <p xml:id="auto_e2rdw82q"><q>How is a pyramid different from a prism?</q></p>
                </li>
                <li xml:id="auto_iqtqtllc">
                    <p xml:id="auto_zw0uhbp0"><q>If you had a prism with the same base and height, how many pyramids would fit inside?</q> (Expected: 3)</p>
                </li>
                <li xml:id="auto_g09zrzdd">
                    <p xml:id="auto_cun366ks"><q>So what fraction of the prism’s volume is one pyramid?</q> (Expected: one-third)</p>
                </li>
            </ul>
        </p>
        <p xml:id="auto_pfsrolxo">
            <alert>Expected Discovery:</alert> Learners should articulate that the volume of a pyramid is one-third the base area times the height.
        </p>
        <p xml:id="auto_pcf90ddm">
            <alert>Support for Struggling Groups:</alert> Say <q>Let us start by finding the base area. Then multiply by the height and divide by 3.</q>
        </p>
        <p xml:id="auto_4spw21cw">
            <alert>Early Finishers:</alert> Ask <q>How would the volume change if the height doubled? If the base dimensions doubled?</q>
        </p>
        <p xml:id="auto_glk6o33m">
            <alert>Sharing:</alert> Identify 2–3 groups with clear findings to share with the class.
        </p>
    </axiom>

            <activity xml:id="auto_9mm6r1vg">
                <statement>
                    <p xml:id="auto_gvt7dwmn">
                        "Pyramid City"
                    </p>
                    <p xml:id="auto_vbk9iq4c">
                        <ul xml:id="auto_iufp3bdt" marker="disc">
                            <li xml:id="auto_chq543pc">
                                <p xml:id="auto_unvv5ikc">
                                     Materials
                                </p>
                                <p xml:id="auto_mcxhbwzt">
                                    🔹 Pictures of famous pyramids (e.g., Egyptian Pyramids, Mayan Pyramids)
                                </p>
                                <p xml:id="auto_r2nw5fg6">
                                   🔹  Measuring tape or rulers (for estimating dimensions)
                                </p>
                                <p xml:id="auto_jxa1bv1n">
                                    🔹 A small model or LEGO pyramid
                                </p>

                            </li>
                        </ul>
                    </p>
                </statement>
            </activity>

            
    <axiom component="lesson-plan">
        <title>Structured Instruction</title>
        <p xml:id="auto_3ianf533">
            <alert>Expected Time:</alert> 10 minutes
        </p>
        <p xml:id="auto_vonzuse2">
            <alert>Transition:</alert> After groups share their findings, formalise the discovery: <q>You discovered that three pyramids fill one prism. That is why the formula has the factor one-third.</q>
        </p>
        <p xml:id="auto_5oxmcdqm">
            <alert>Key Teaching Points:</alert>
        </p>
        <p xml:id="auto_ouw5lp7b">
            <ul>
                <li xml:id="auto_bnohm64p">
                    <p xml:id="auto_rk4n4qn1">Clearly distinguish between height (perpendicular from base to apex) and slant height (along a face). Use a diagram to show both.</p>
                </li>
                <li xml:id="auto_rbx7r17x">
                    <p xml:id="auto_hrz3iiwz">Emphasise the two-step process: (1) Find the base area using the correct polygon formula, (2) Multiply by height and divide by 3.</p>
                </li>
                <li xml:id="auto_rpqwbc8d">
                    <p xml:id="auto_69rpme90">Remind learners that pyramids can have any polygonal base (square, rectangular, triangular, pentagonal, etc.).</p>
                </li>
            </ul>
        </p>
    </axiom>

    <insight xml:id="auto_j5ztbnpl">
                <p xml:id="auto_iyc40jov">
                    <term>What is a Pyramid?</term> A pyramid is a three-dimensional solid with a polygonal base and triangular faces that meet at a single point called the apex.
                </p>
                <p xml:id="auto_9hqywnxf">
                    <term>Formula:</term>
                </p>
                <p xml:id="auto_w9pthbdk">
                    Volume of a Pyramid <m>= \frac{1}{3} \times</m> Base Area <m>\times h</m>
                </p>
                <p xml:id="auto_dzfwgrbs">
                    where:
                </p>
                <p xml:id="auto_91123u1b">
                    <ol marker="(i)">
                        <li xml:id="auto_u36e0i89">
                            <p xml:id="auto_xdnbq6y2">
                                Base Area is the area of the polygonal base
                            </p>
                        </li>
                        <li xml:id="auto_k6xn5c62">
                            <p xml:id="auto_6z8cmzp3">
                                <m>h</m> is the height of the pyramid (perpendicular distance from base to apex)
                            </p>
                        </li>
                    </ol>
                </p>
                <p xml:id="auto_uuvxscrg">
                   Why <m>\frac{1}{3}</m> ?
                </p>
                <p xml:id="auto_tpmhn4c0">
                    Three pyramids with the same base and height fit exactly inside a prism with the same base and height. Therefore, the volume of a pyramid is one-third the volume of a prism.
                </p>
                <p xml:id="auto_uzih5mn1">
                    <term>Types of Pyramids Based on Base Shape:</term>
                </p>
                <p xml:id="auto_expy00tz">
                    <ol marker="(a)">
                        <li xml:id="auto_uzdjjeuv">
                            <p xml:id="auto_n4n4hfse">
                                Square pyramid: Base is a square.
                            </p>
                        </li>
                        <li xml:id="auto_2nw7v3zi">
                            <p xml:id="auto_yvfa2n3p">
                                Rectangular pyramid: Base is a rectangle.
                            </p>
                        </li>
                        <li xml:id="auto_mu0a5guu">
                            <p xml:id="auto_u43z1py0">
                                Triangular pyramid: Base is a triangle.
                            </p>
                        </li>
                        <li xml:id="auto_eepzcoc8">
                            <p xml:id="auto_2mzfe3cx">
                                Pentagonal pyramid: Base is a pentagon.
                            </p>
                        </li>
                    </ol>
                </p>
                <p xml:id="auto_2wrtpyd9">
                    <term>Scaffolding Strategies to Address Misconceptions:</term>
                </p>
                <tabular left="medium" right="medium" top="medium" bottom="medium">
                    <row header="yes">
                        <cell>Misconception</cell>
                        <cell>Clarification</cell>
                    </row>
                    <row>
                        <cell>A pyramid is the same as a prism</cell>
                        <cell>No, a pyramid has triangular faces that meet at an apex, while a prism has two parallel bases</cell>
                    </row>
                    <row>
                        <cell>The volume formula is Base Area <m>\times</m> height</cell>
                        <cell> No, you must multiply by <m>\frac{1}{3}</m> The formula is <m>\frac{1}{3} \times</m> Base Area <m>\times</m> height.</cell>
                    </row>
                    <row>
                        <cell>The height is the slant height</cell>
                        <cell>No, the height is the perpendicular distance from the base to the apex, not the slant height along the face</cell>
                    </row>
                    <row>
                        <cell>All pyramids have square bases</cell>
                        <cell>No, pyramids can have any polygonal base (triangle, rectangle, pentagon, etc.)</cell>
                    </row>
                </tabular>
            </insight>


    <axiom component="lesson-plan">
        <title>Practice and Application</title>
        <p xml:id="auto_mhur156g">
            <alert>Expected Time:</alert> 10 minutes
        </p>
        <p xml:id="auto_xf7noea4">
            <alert>Teacher Guidance:</alert> Work through examples using the two-step approach. Encourage learners to write the base area calculation and volume calculation as separate steps.
        </p>
        <p xml:id="auto_to56paoj">
            <alert>Monitoring:</alert> Circulate during practice. Watch for learners who:
        </p>
        <p xml:id="auto_5wkej2b0">
            <ul>
                <li xml:id="auto_liyj8s7h">
                    <p xml:id="auto_3xogzw6e">Forget to multiply by <m>\frac{1}{3}</m> (using the prism formula instead).</p>
                </li>
                <li xml:id="auto_kqyfhnji">
                    <p xml:id="auto_ta747dec">Confuse the height of the pyramid with the slant height.</p>
                </li>
                <li xml:id="auto_38wa4tda">
                    <p xml:id="auto_v3kmi8b0">Use the wrong base area formula for the given base shape.</p>
                </li>
            </ul>
        </p>
    </axiom>

            <p xml:id="auto_e8zyygn1">
             A pyramid has a polygonal base and triangular faces that meet at the apex.   
            </p>
        <example xml:id="auto_9cb6bkl0">
        <statement>

            <sidebyside>
        <p xml:id="auto_zx3tcp25">
            Find the volume of a square pyramid with a height of 6 cm and a side length of 10cm.
        </p> 
        <image width="50%">
        <latex-image label="square-pyramid-volume">
            \begin{tikzpicture}
               % Define vertices of the tetrahedron
                \coordinate (A) at (-1,2,0);  % Bottom-left vertex of the base
                \coordinate (B) at (6,0,0);  % Bottom-right vertex of the base
                \coordinate (C) at (3,5,0);  % Top vertex of the base
                \coordinate (D) at (3,2.5,10);  % Apex of the tetrahedron
                \coordinate (H) at (4.5,1.25,5);  % Intersection of line BD with the perpendicular from C

                % Draw base triangle
                \draw[thick] (A) -- (B) -- (C) -- cycle;
                
                % Draw edges from the base to the apex
                \draw[thick] (A) -- (D);
                \draw[thick] (C) -- (D);
                
                % Draw perpendicular from C to BD
                \draw[dashed] (C) -- (H);
                \draw[thick] (B) -- (H) -- (D);

                
                % Draw right angle at H
                \draw (H) ++(0.2,0) -- ++(0,0.2) -- ++(-0.2,0);
                
                % Label base side
                \draw[|&lt;-&gt;|] (H) -- (C) node[midway, below] {6 cm};
                \draw[|&lt;-&gt;|] (B) -- (D) node[midway, below] {10 cm};
                
                
                % Label vertices
                \node[below left] at (A) {A};
                \node[below right] at (B) {B};
                \node[above] at (C) {C};
                \node[below] at (D) {D};
            \end{tikzpicture}
        </latex-image>
        </image>  
    </sidebyside>
        </statement>
        <solution>
            <p xml:id="auto_52nc3num">
                Step 1: Select the correct formula and substitute the given values.
            </p>
            <p xml:id="auto_7am4t1nn">
                We are given b = 10 and H = 6, therefore
                <md>
                    <mrow> V = \amp \frac{1}{3} \times \text{base Area}  </mrow>
                    <mrow> \text{Base Area} =\amp (10 \text{cm} \times 10 \text{cm}) </mrow>
                        <mrow> = \amp \frac {1}{3} \times (10 \times 10) \text{cm}^2 \times 6\text{cm} </mrow>
                        <mrow> = \amp 100 \text{cm}^2 \times 2 \text{cm} </mrow>
                        <mrow> = \amp 200 \text{cm}^3 </mrow>
                </md>
            </p>
            <p xml:id="auto_opztz8yc">
               The volume of the square pyramid is <m>200 \text{cm}^3</m>. 
            </p>
        </solution>

    </example> 
        
        <example xml:id="auto_k4ep5wni">
            <statement>
                <p xml:id="auto_ruw9p7nq">
                   A square pyramid has a base of 6 cm × 6 cm and a height of 9 cm. Find it's volume. 
                </p>
            </statement>
            <solution>
                <p xml:id="auto_vq25lrxk">
                    <md>
                        <mrow>V = \amp \frac{1}{3} \times \text{base Area} \times h</mrow>
                        <mrow> \text{Base Area} =\amp (6 \text{cm} \times 6 \, \text{cm}) </mrow>
                        <mrow> = \amp \frac {1}{3} \times (6 \times 6) \, \text{cm} \times 9 \, \text{cm}</mrow>
                        <mrow> = \amp \frac{1}{3} \times 36\, \text{cm}^2 \times 9 \, \text{cm} </mrow>
                        <mrow> = \amp 108 \, \text{cm}^3 </mrow>

                    </md>
                </p>
            </solution>
        </example>
        <example xml:id="auto_2fegdbdb">
            <statement>
                <p xml:id="auto_6zzzfxei">
                    A triangular pyramid has a base of 5 cm × 8 cm and a height of 10 cm.
                </p>

            </statement>
            <solution>
                <p xml:id="auto_tz0dpo5y">
                     <md>
                        <mrow>V = \amp \frac{1}{3} \times \text{base Area} \times h</mrow>
                        <mrow> \text{Base Area} = \amp(\frac {1}{2} \times 5\, \text{cm}\times 8 \,\text{cm}) </mrow>
                        <mrow> = \amp \frac {1}{3} \times ( \frac {1}{2} \times 5 \,\text{cm} \times 8 \, \text{cm}) \times 10\, \text{cm} </mrow>
                        <mrow> = \amp \frac{1}{3} \times 20 \,\text{cm}^2 \times 10 \,\text{cm} </mrow>
                        <mrow> = \amp 66.67\, \text{cm}^3 </mrow>

                    </md>    

                </p>
            </solution>
        </example>
        <example xml:id="auto_htgbqgxd">
            <statement>
                <p xml:id="auto_6qkojy7y">
                    A pyramid has a rectangular base of 4 m by 6 m and a height of 12 m.
                </p>
                
            </statement>
            <solution>
                <p xml:id="auto_dvk0kkdx">
                     <md>
                        <mrow>V = \amp \frac{1}{3} \times \text{base Area} \times h</mrow>
                        <mrow> \text{Base Area} = \amp( \times 4\, \text{m}\times 6\,\text{m}) </mrow>
                        <mrow> = \amp \frac {1}{3} \times\times( 4 \,\text{m} \times 6 \,\text{m}) \times 12 </mrow>
                        <mrow> = \amp \frac{1}{3} \times 24\, \text{m}^2 \times 12 \,\text{m} </mrow>
                        <mrow> = \amp 96 \,\text{m}^3 </mrow>

                    </md>    

                </p>
            </solution>
        </example>

    <axiom component="lesson-plan">
        <title>Assessment – Exit Ticket</title>
        <p xml:id="auto_3cxpyp0g">
            <alert>Expected Time:</alert> 5 minutes
        </p>
        <p xml:id="auto_y9wajnf1">
            Learners complete individually to demonstrate understanding.
        </p>
        <p xml:id="auto_dwkdnybv">
            <alert>Question 1:</alert> A pyramid has a square base with a side length of <m>6</m> cm. The height of the pyramid is <m>9</m> cm. Find the volume.
        </p>
        <p xml:id="auto_egrgf4w4">
            <alert>Question 2:</alert> A pyramid-shaped tent has a rectangular base of <m>8</m> m by <m>6</m> m and a height of <m>5</m> m. Find the volume of air inside the tent.
        </p>
        <p xml:id="auto_lrsanaze">
            <alert>Question 3:</alert> A pyramid has a square base with each side measuring <m>10</m> cm. The height of the pyramid is <m>15</m> cm. Find the volume.
        </p>
        <p xml:id="auto_2uagskrg">
            <alert>Answer Key:</alert>
        </p>
        <p xml:id="auto_2uimy5w7">
            <alert>Q1:</alert> <m>V = \frac{1}{3} \times 6^2 \times 9 = \frac{1}{3} \times 36 \times 9 = 108 \; \text{cm}^3</m>.
        </p>
        <p xml:id="auto_b8sktuss">
            <alert>Q2:</alert> <m>V = \frac{1}{3} \times (8 \times 6) \times 5 = \frac{1}{3} \times 48 \times 5 = 80 \; \text{m}^3</m>.
        </p>
        <p xml:id="auto_rwhzr0id">
            <alert>Q3:</alert> <m>V = \frac{1}{3} \times 10^2 \times 15 = \frac{1}{3} \times 100 \times 15 = 500 \; \text{cm}^3</m>.
        </p>
    </axiom>

    <exercises>
        <exercise>
            <statement>
                <p>
                    A pyramid has a square base with a side length of <m>6</m> cm. The height of the pyramid is <m>9</m> cm.
                </p>
                <image width="50%">
                <latex-image label="square-pyramid-volume-one-exercise">
                    \begin{tikzpicture}
                    % Define vertices of the tetrahedron
                        \coordinate (A) at (-1,2,0);  % Bottom-left vertex of the base
                        \coordinate (B) at (6,0,0);  % Bottom-right vertex of the base
                        \coordinate (C) at (3,5,0);  % Top vertex of the base
                        \coordinate (D) at (3,2.5,10);  % Apex of the tetrahedron
                        \coordinate (H) at (4.5,1.25,5);  % Intersection of line BD with the perpendicular from C

                        % Draw base triangle
                        \draw[thick] (A) -- (B) -- (C) -- cycle;
                        
                    % Draw base triangle
                        \draw[thick] (A) -- (B) -- (C) -- cycle;
                        \draw[thick] (A) --(B) --(D) --cycle;
                        \draw[thick] (B) --(D) --(C) --cycle;
                        
                        
                        % Draw perpendicular from C to BD
                        \draw[dashed] (C) -- (H);
                        \draw[thick] (B) -- (H) -- (D);

                        
                        % Draw right angle at H
                        \draw [thin](H) ++(0.2,0) -- ++(0,0.2) -- ++(-0.2,0);
                        
                        % Label base side
                        \draw[|&lt;-&gt;|] (H) -- (C) node[midway, below] {6 cm};
                        \draw[|&lt;-&gt;|] (B) -- (D) node[midway, below] {9 cm};
                        
                        
                        % Label vertices
                        \node[below left] at (A) {A};
                        \node[below right] at (B) {B};
                        \node[above] at (C) {C};
                        \node[below] at (D) {D};
                    \end{tikzpicture}
                </latex-image>
                </image> 
            </statement>
            <answer>
                <p>
                    <m>108 \;\text{cm}^3</m>
                </p>
            </answer>
        </exercise>
        <exercise>
            <statement>
                <p>
                     A pyramid-shaped tent has a rectangular base of 8 m by 6 m and a height of 5 m. Find the volume of air inside the tent. 
                </p>
            </statement>
            <answer>
                <p>
                   <m>80 \;\text{m}^3</m> 
                </p>
            </answer>
        </exercise>
        <exercise>
            <statement>
                <p>
                   A pyramid has a square base with each side measuring 10 cm. The height of the pyramid is 15 cm. 
                </p>
                <image width="50%">
                <latex-image label="square-pyramid-exercise-volume-two">
                    \begin{tikzpicture}
                    % Define vertices of the tetrahedron
                        \coordinate (A) at (-1,2,0);  % Bottom-left vertex of the base
                        \coordinate (B) at (6,0,0);  % Bottom-right vertex of the base
                        \coordinate (C) at (3,5,0);  % Top vertex of the base
                        \coordinate (D) at (3,2.5,10);  % Apex of the tetrahedron
                        \coordinate (H) at (4.5,1.25,5);  % Intersection of line BD with the perpendicular from C

                        % Draw base triangle
                        \draw[thick] (A) -- (B) -- (C) -- cycle;
                        \draw[thick] (A) --(B) --(D) --cycle;
                        \draw[thick] (B) --(D) --(C) --cycle;
                        % Draw edges from the base to the apex
                        \draw[thick] (A) -- (D);
                        \draw[thick] (C) -- (D);
                        
                        % Draw perpendicular from C to BD
                        \draw[dashed] (C) -- (H);
                        \draw[thick] (B) -- (H) -- (D) --cycle;

                        
                        % Draw right angle at H
                        \draw [thin,blue](H) ++(0.2,0) -- ++(0,0.2) -- ++(-0.2,0);
                        
                        % Label base side
                        \draw[|&lt;-&gt;|] (H) -- (C) node[midway, below] {10 cm};
                        \draw[|&lt;-&gt;|] (B) -- (D) node[midway, below] {15 cm};
                        
                        
                        % Label vertices
                        \node[below left] at (A) {A};
                        \node[below right] at (B) {B};
                        \node[above] at (C) {C};
                        \node[below] at (D) {D};
                    \end{tikzpicture}
                </latex-image>
                </image> 
            </statement>
            <answer>
                <p>
                    <m>500 \;\text{cm}^3</m>
                </p>
            </answer>
        </exercise>
        <exercise>
            <statement>
                <p>
                    A pyramid has a triangular base where the base of the triangle is 8 cm and the height of the triangle is 6 cm. The height of the pyramid is 10 cm.
                </p>
                <image width="50%">
                <latex-image label="square-pyramid-exercise-volume">
                    \begin{tikzpicture}
                    % Define vertices of the tetrahedron
                        \coordinate (A) at (-1,2,0);  % Bottom-left vertex of the base
                        \coordinate (B) at (6,0,0);  % Bottom-right vertex of the base
                        \coordinate (C) at (3,5,0);  % Top vertex of the base
                        \coordinate (D) at (3,2.5,10);  % Apex of the tetrahedron
                        \coordinate (H) at (4.5,1.25,5);  % Intersection of line BD with the perpendicular from C

                        % Draw base triangle
                        \draw[thick] (A) -- (B) -- (C) -- cycle;
                        \draw[thick] (A) --(B) --(D) --cycle;
                        \draw[thick] (B) --(D) --(C) --cycle;
                        
                        % Draw edges from the base to the apex
                        \draw[thick] (A) -- (D);
                        \draw[thick] (C) -- (D);
                        
                        % Draw perpendicular from C to BD
                        \draw[dashed] (C) -- (H);
                        \draw[thick] (B) -- (H) -- (D);

                        
                        % Draw right angle at H
                        \draw (H) ++(0.2,0) -- ++(0,0.2) -- ++(-0.2,0);
                        
                        % Label base side
                        \draw[|&lt;-&gt;|] (H) -- (C) node[midway, below] {8 cm};
                        \draw[|&lt;-&gt;|] (B) -- (D) node[midway, below] {10 cm};
                        
                        
                        % Label vertices
                        \node[below left] at (A) {A};
                        \node[below right] at (B) {B};
                        \node[above] at (C) {C};
                        \node[below] at (D) {D};
                    \end{tikzpicture}
                </latex-image>
                </image> 
            </statement>
            <answer>
                <p>
                    <m>80 \;\text{cm}^3</m>
                </p>
            </answer>
        </exercise>
        <exercise>
            <statement>
                <p>
                   A decorative garden pyramid has a square base with each side measuring 4 m. The height of the pyramid is 3 m. 
                </p>
            </statement>
            <statement>
                <p>
                    <m>16 \;\text{m}^3</m>
                </p>
            </statement>
        </exercise>
    </exercises>
     <xi:include href="../../resources-checkpoint.ptx" />

